  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Food Security Program with Salesian Missions- Haiti- 2013</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">School feeding, rehabilitation, crisis relief</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Your meals will support the holistic work of Salesian Missions in Haiti. The Salesian work is a three step program in Cite Soleil, Haiti, to socially and economically rehabilitate street children. Cite Soleil is one of the most dangerous neighborhoods in Haiti, and armed gangs are in control of most of the area behind the Salesian complex. During the first stage of the program, the Salesians get to know the youth who live on the streets, especially the young women who are working in prostitution. Between 200-300 students come to the second stage house every day, because it is a safe place where they can get what is usually their only cooked meal of the day. Students at Lakou participate in workshops to learn trades, and are also invited to stay over one night per week. The third stage consists of dormitories, classrooms, and workshops where the Salesians house and care for 150 students: educating them, teaching them a trade, feeding them three meals a day, and taking steps to reconcile the students with their families.</narrative>
  </description>
